So no matter from which side we are persisting we need to set the primary key of inverse side to the owning side .. that is employee.setdepartment(this) ..right
________________________________________
1️⃣ Core Rule of JPA Relationships
In a bidirectional relationship, only the owning side controls the database relationship.
In your example:
Department  → inverse side
Employee    → owning side
Because Employee has:
@ManyToOne
@JoinColumn(name = "dept_id")
private Department department;
So the foreign key dept_id exists in the Employee table.
________________________________________
2️⃣ What Must Be Set Before Persisting
To persist the relationship correctly, the owning side must be set.
So this is mandatory:
employee.setDepartment(department);
This tells Hibernate:
employee.dept_id = department.id
________________________________________
3️⃣ If Persisting From Department Side
Even if you start saving from the inverse side, you still must update the owning side.
Example:
public void addEmployee(Employee employee) {
    employees.add(employee);
    employee.setDepartment(this);   // VERY IMPORTANT
}
Why?
Because Department cannot update the FK column.
Only Employee can.
________________________________________
4️⃣ What Happens If You Don't Set Owning Side
Example:
department.getEmployees().add(employee);
departmentRepository.save(department);
But if you do not set:
employee.setDepartment(department)
Then Hibernate will insert:
employee.dept_id = null
So the relationship will not be created in DB.
________________________________________
5️⃣ Correct Bidirectional Helper Method
Best practice:
public void addEmployee(Employee employee) {
    this.employees.add(employee);
    employee.setDepartment(this);
}
This ensures:
Department.employees → updated
Employee.department  → updated
Both sides stay in sync.
________________________________________
6️⃣ Important Clarification About Your Statement
You said:
"set the primary key of inverse side to the owning side"
Slight correction:
You are not setting the primary key directly.
You are setting the entity reference, and Hibernate internally uses the primary key.
Example:
employee.setDepartment(department);
Hibernate internally converts it to:
employee.dept_id = department.id
________________________________________
7️⃣ Golden Rule (Very Important)
Always remember this rule:
Owning side decides the relationship in database.
So owning side must be set before persisting.
________________________________________
8️⃣ Final Summary
✔ Relationship is stored in owning side table
✔ Owning side contains foreign key
✔ Always set owning side before save
Example:
employee.setDepartment(department);
employeeRepository.save(employee);
Even when persisting from Department:
department.addEmployee(employee);
departmentRepository.save(department);
Internally this works because:
employee.setDepartment(department)
________________________________________
