So then what is the use of cascade here that is in inverse side that is department we are using cascade.CASCADETYPE.ALL ….?

Good question 👍. This is a very common confusion in JPA.
You are asking:
If Employee (owning side) controls the relationship, then what is the use of
cascade = CascadeType.ALL on the inverse side (Department)?
Let's clarify this step by step.
________________________________________
1️⃣ What Cascade Actually Does
Cascade does NOT control the relationship.
Cascade only controls operation propagation.
Meaning:
If an operation happens on Parent,
the same operation should happen on Child.
Example operations:
•	PERSIST
•	MERGE
•	REMOVE
•	REFRESH
•	DETACH
So cascade simply means:
propagate operations to related entities
________________________________________
2️⃣ Example Without Cascade
Entities:
@OneToMany(mappedBy = "department")
private List<Employee> employees;
Code:
Department dept = new Department();
dept.setName("IT");

Employee emp = new Employee();
emp.setName("Ravi");

emp.setDepartment(dept);

dept.getEmployees().add(emp);

departmentRepository.save(dept);
What happens?
❌ Only Department gets saved
❌ Employee will not be saved
Because cascade is not enabled.
________________________________________
3️⃣ Example With Cascade
@OneToMany(mappedBy = "department", cascade = CascadeType.ALL)
private List<Employee> employees;
Now when you do:
departmentRepository.save(dept);
Hibernate automatically does:
save(department)
save(employee1)
save(employee2)
save(employee3)
So one save triggers many saves.
________________________________________
4️⃣ Important Point
Cascade does not change owning side rules.
You still must set:
employee.setDepartment(department);
Cascade will not fix relationship mapping.
It only ensures child entities are also persisted.
________________________________________
5️⃣ Why We Put Cascade On Department
Because Department is logically the parent.
Example:
Department
   |
   |---- Employee
   |---- Employee
   |---- Employee
So operations should propagate:
Save Department → Save Employees
Delete Department → Delete Employees
________________________________________
6️⃣ Example Delete Case
If we use:
cascade = CascadeType.ALL
Then:
departmentRepository.delete(dept);
Hibernate executes:
delete employees
delete department
Without cascade:
❌ Foreign key constraint error.
________________________________________
7️⃣ Real World Example
Think of:
Order → OrderItems
When you save Order, all OrderItems should be saved.
save(order)
Should automatically do:
save(orderItem1)
save(orderItem2)
save(orderItem3)
That is what cascade does.
________________________________________
8️⃣ Relationship Control vs Cascade
Concept	Responsibility
Owning Side	Controls foreign key
Cascade	Propagates operations
Inverse Side	Just mapping reference
________________________________________
9️⃣ Final Flow In Your Example
When you write:
department.addEmployee(emp);
departmentRepository.save(department);
Internally:
employee.setDepartment(department)   ← relationship
cascade persist                      ← saves employee
Both are needed.
________________________________________
🔑 Final Key Point
Owning side → controls relationship (FK)
Cascade → controls persistence propagation
These are two completely different responsibilities.
________________________________________

What if employeerepository.save()….?

Good follow-up 👍. Let's see what happens if you call employeeRepository.save(employee) instead of saving the department.
________________________________________
1️⃣ If You Save From Employee Side (Owning Side)
Example:
Employee emp = new Employee();
emp.setName("Ravi");
emp.setSalary(50000);

Department dept = departmentRepository.findById(1L).get();

emp.setDepartment(dept);

employeeRepository.save(emp);
Hibernate SQL:
insert into employee (name, salary, dept_id)
values ('Ravi', 50000, 1);
✔ Employee saved
✔ dept_id is stored
✔ Relationship created
Because Employee is the owning side.
________________________________________
2️⃣ Does Cascade From Department Matter Here?
No ❌
This cascade:
@OneToMany(mappedBy = "department", cascade = CascadeType.ALL)
is only useful when you save Department.
When you do:
employeeRepository.save(emp);
cascade on Department side will NOT be triggered.
Cascade only works from the entity on which the operation is called.
________________________________________
3️⃣ If Department Is New (Not Saved Yet)
Example:
Department dept = new Department();
dept.setName("IT");

Employee emp = new Employee();
emp.setName("Ravi");

emp.setDepartment(dept);

employeeRepository.save(emp);
What happens?
❌ Error:
TransientPropertyValueException
object references an unsaved transient instance
Because department is not persisted.
________________________________________
4️⃣ How To Fix That
You must either:
Option 1 — Save Department First
departmentRepository.save(dept);

emp.setDepartment(dept);
employeeRepository.save(emp);
________________________________________
Option 2 — Cascade From Employee Side
@ManyToOne(cascade = CascadeType.PERSIST)
@JoinColumn(name = "dept_id")
private Department department;
Then:
employeeRepository.save(emp);
will also save the department.
But this is not recommended in many designs, because:
Many employees might share the same department.
________________________________________
5️⃣ Real Project Practice
Most APIs do this:
Department dept = departmentRepository.findById(dto.getDepartmentId());

employee.setDepartment(dept);

employeeRepository.save(employee);
Department already exists.
________________________________________
6️⃣ Summary
Scenario	Result
employeeRepository.save(employee)	Works (owning side)
departmentRepository.save(department)	Needs cascade to save employees
department not saved	Error
cascade on Department	Works only when saving Department
cascade on Employee	Works when saving Employee
________________________________________
7️⃣ Simple Rule
Save from owning side → relationship works directly
Save from inverse side → need cascade
________________________________________
